 whose ideas about brokerage politics have influenced a generation of scholars. The contributors explore four thematic pathways: How does brokerage work across lines of division in society? How do partisan teams hold together in the face of the centrifugal pressures that necessitate brokerage? How can parties withstand the complicated principal-agent relations that inevitably arise? And, how does the institutional context constrain a multitude of competing interests when it, itself, is quite fragile? By providing new perspectives on parties as organizations that exist within political systems and by raising key questions about the sustainability of brokerage politics, this volume will provoke theoretical reconsideration, prompt further integrative thinking, and inspire future research at the political organization-system nexus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical parties. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAttanasio, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAucoin, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakvis, Herman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardi, Luciano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarty, R. Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourtney, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCross, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaute, Emilie Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHazan, Reuven Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g